support.p:
The Basler Handschrift is a paper manuscript with a yellow parchment binding cover.
                                    From a codicological point of view, it can be divided into three units with different watermarks:
                                    the first one, from fol. 1 to fol. 218, has a crown beneath a pointed trefoil; 
                                    the second one, from fol. 219 to fol. 223, has an ox head;
                                    the third one, from fol. 224 to fol. 231, has a wheel.

supportDesc.foliation:
Foliation: We find three different types of pagination numbering, which are not related to the three codicological units: 
                                 firstly, a modern numbering on the top right corner of the recto leaves, which comprises the whole manuscript; 
                                 secondly, at the same place, an older numbering applied in 1844, which covers only the last 52 leaves and starts after the end of SW, counting current fol. 180 as fol. 1; 
                                 finally, the first 100 leaves of the manuscript are counted with centered red numbers on the bottom of the leaves (always on the recto side).
